    <h3>The Hidden Costs Nobody Tells You About</h3>

    <p>The sticker price of the machine is only part of the total cost. Build these into your budget:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>GST:</strong> 18% on most commercial bakery equipment. This is not optional and cannot be avoided if buying from a registered supplier (which you should be).</li>
      <li><strong>Installation and commissioning:</strong> ₹3,000 – ₹25,000 per machine depending on complexity. Often quoted separately from the machine price.</li>
      <li><strong>Civil work:</strong> Electrical panel upgrades, gas line extensions, exhaust duct fabrication, drainage — budget ₹30,000 – ₹2 lakh depending on your existing infrastructure.</li>
      <li><strong>Freight and transport:</strong> For heavy equipment (ovens, large mixers), delivery from Delhi/Mumbai/Chennai to Tier-2 cities can add ₹5,000 – ₹40,000.</li>
      <li><strong>AMC (Annual Maintenance Contract):</strong> 6–10% of machine value per year. Factor this into year 2 and 3 operating costs.</li>
      <li><strong>Consumables and accessories:</strong> Baking trays, silicone mats, rack trolleys, spare heating elements — these add up to ₹30,000 – ₹2 lakh for a fully equipped setup.</li>
      <li><strong>Staff training:</strong> Some suppliers charge for training; others include it. Budget for 2–3 days of commissioning and training time regardless.</li>
    </ul>

    <p><strong>Rule of thumb:</strong> Add 25–35% to the total equipment sticker price to arrive at the fully installed, operational cost.</p>

