    <h2>Step 6: Delivery and Installation Checklist</h2>

    <p>The day equipment arrives is high-risk. Damage in transit, missing components, incorrect installation — all of these are far easier to resolve before the supplier leaves your premises than after. Use this checklist on delivery day.</p>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Checkpoint</th><th>What to Verify</th><th>Status</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Packaging condition</td><td>Inspect all packaging for damage before signing the delivery receipt. Photograph any damaged packaging.</td><td>☐</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Model and serial number</td><td>Match the model number and serial number on the machine against your purchase order and invoice.</td><td>☐</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Complete accessories</td><td>Check all trays, racks, baking stones, steam hoses, control panels, and accessories listed in the invoice are present.</td><td>☐</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Manuals and documentation</td><td>Receive operation manual (English or Hindi), maintenance schedule, and spare parts catalogue.</td><td>☐</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Warranty card</td><td>Warranty card filled out with serial number, installation date, and supplier stamp — keep this. It's your legal document.</td><td>☐</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Electrical connection</td><td>Confirm power requirement (voltage, phase, amperage) before plugging in. An incorrect connection voids warranty.</td><td>☐</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Levelling</td><td>All ovens and mixers must be levelled on-site. Verify with a spirit level — unlevel ovens bake unevenly.</td><td>☐</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Temperature calibration</td><td>Run the oven at 180°C and verify with an oven thermometer. Document the reading at installation.</td><td>☐</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Steam function test (if applicable)</td><td>Inject steam and verify the system operates; check all steam nozzles for blockages.</td><td>☐</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Controls and timers</td><td>Test every programmable function — all temperature programs, timer settings, fan speed options.</td><td>☐</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Ventilation clearance</td><td>Verify the required clearance on all sides is maintained; exhaust duct properly connected and functional.</td><td>☐</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Trial bake</td><td>Bake a test batch on-site before the installation engineer leaves. This is the most important step.</td><td>☐</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Operator training</td><td>Ensure the staff who will operate the equipment receives a proper demonstration from the installation engineer.</td><td>☐</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Service contact details</td><td>Get the name, mobile number, and email of the local service engineer — not just the supplier's main number.</td><td>☐</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Signed installation report</td><td>Get a signed installation completion report from the engineer. This starts your warranty clock officially.</td><td>☐</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p><strong>Do not pay the balance installation amount until the trial bake is completed satisfactorily.</strong> This is the only leverage you have to ensure the installation is done properly.</p>

    <h2>Step 7: Warranty Terms to Insist On</h2>

    <p>In India, bakery equipment warranty terms vary enormously between suppliers. The standard offering is often inadequate — here's what you should insist on, and what to watch out for.</p>

    <h3>Minimum Acceptable Warranty Terms</h3>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Equipment Type</th><th>Minimum Warranty Period</th><th>What Should Be Covered</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Commercial ovens (convection, deck)</td><td>2 years (parts and labour)</td><td>Heating elements, thermostats, control board, fan motor, door hinges and seals</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Rotary rack ovens</td><td>2 years (parts and labour)</td><td>Burner assembly, heat exchanger, rotation mechanism, control system</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Commercial mixers</td><td>2 years (parts and labour)</td><td>Motor, gearbox, bowl lift mechanism, speed control</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Refrigeration equipment</td><td>2 years (parts), 5 years (compressor)</td><td>Compressor (5-year is industry standard), refrigerant system, evaporator, condenser</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Dough proofers</td><td>1 year minimum</td><td>Heating element, humidity system, thermostat</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Dough sheeters and moulders</td><td>1 year minimum</td><td>Drive motor, rollers, belt mechanism</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>Warranty Clauses to Watch For (Red Flags)</h3>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>"Warranty does not cover heating elements"</strong> — Heating elements are a primary failure point on ovens. If they're excluded, the warranty covers almost nothing meaningful. Push back.</li>
      <li><strong>"Warranty void if serviced by third party"</strong> — Acceptable only if the supplier commits in writing to a maximum service response time (e.g., 48 hours). Otherwise, this clause traps you.</li>
      <li><strong>"Parts warranty only, labour charged separately"</strong> — Labour charges for warranty repairs can exceed part costs. Insist on parts AND labour coverage.</li>
      <li><strong>"Warranty does not cover normal wear"</strong> — Vague language that allows the supplier to reject almost any claim. Ask them to define exactly what "normal wear" excludes — it should be items like door gaskets after 12 months, not thermostats and motors.</li>
      <li><strong>Warranty card that doesn't specify start date</strong> — The warranty should start from the installation date, not the shipping date or invoice date. Get the installation date written on the warranty card.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>What to Ask For in Writing Before Signing</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>The maximum response time for service calls (by city or region)</li>
      <li>The process for raising a warranty claim (phone, email, portal)</li>
      <li>Escalation path if the first service response is inadequate</li>
      <li>Policy on loaner/replacement equipment if your machine is down for more than 5 working days</li>
      <li>Confirmation that the warranty is transferable if you sell the bakery (relevant for resale value)</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Step 8: Common Buying Mistakes and How to Avoid Them</h2>

    <p>After working with hundreds of bakeries across India, these are the procurement mistakes that come up again and again:</p>

    <h3>Mistake 1: Buying on Price Alone</h3>
    <p>The cheapest oven in the market is often the cheapest for a reason — poor build quality, no local service, missing spare parts. A ₹70,000 oven that breaks down twice a year and has a 3-week repair turnaround will cost you far more in lost production and emergency repairs than a ₹1.1 lakh oven that runs for 7 years without issue. Calculate total cost of ownership, not just sticker price.</p>

    <h3>Mistake 2: Over-Buying Capacity</h3>
    <p>A 20-tray convection oven running at 30% capacity uses the same electricity as one running at 90% capacity. Over-buying wastes capital and inflates your running costs. Buy for your 6–12 month projected volume, not your 5-year dream. You can always add capacity later — and by then, your cash flow will support it.</p>

    <h3>Mistake 3: Ignoring the After-Sales Service Network</h3>
    <p>The equipment that works is less important than the service that fixes it when it stops working. A premium European brand with no service engineer within 500 km of your city is a worse choice than a mid-range brand with a trained service team 10 km away. Always verify the service network before committing to any brand.</p>

    <h3>Mistake 4: Not Verifying Electrical Infrastructure First</h3>
    <p>A 20-tray convection oven can draw 12–18 kW. A full-rack rotary oven can draw 35–50 kW. Many Indian commercial kitchens have electrical infrastructure that cannot support this load. Getting a load sanction from DISCOM can take weeks or months. Verify your electrical capacity before ordering equipment, not after.</p>

    <h3>Mistake 5: Paying 100% Advance Without Legal Recourse</h3>
    <p>Never pay 100% of the invoice amount before the equipment is delivered and installed to your satisfaction. If a supplier insists on 100% advance, ask for a bank guarantee or post-dated cheque arrangement. Always retain 10–20% as a retention amount until the installation is complete and a trial bake is successfully done.</p>

    <h3>Mistake 6: Buying All Equipment from One Supplier by Default</h3>
    <p>Convenience is tempting, but a single-supplier bundle often means you pay a premium on 2–3 items to get a discount on 1. Evaluate each major equipment category independently. Sometimes the best oven supplier is different from the best mixer supplier. Bundle strategically, not by default.</p>

    <h3>Mistake 7: Forgetting to Plan for Consumables and Accessories</h3>
    <p>An oven without enough baking trays is half an oven. A mixer without bowl scrapers and dough hooks for different applications limits your menu. The accessories budget — trays, racks, trolleys, proofing baskets, silicone mats — should be part of the initial equipment budget, not an afterthought.</p>

    <h3>Mistake 8: Buying Used Equipment Without Inspection</h3>
    <p>Used equipment can be excellent value, but only if you can inspect it operating under load before purchase. A non-working oven on display at a used equipment dealer tells you almost nothing. Always insist on seeing the machine bake before you pay. Read our full guide: <a href="/blog/used-bakery-equipment-guide">Used Bakery Equipment: What to Check Before You Buy</a>.</p>

    <h3>Mistake 9: No Written Delivery Date</h3>
    <p>Many bakeries miss their planned launch date because equipment arrived weeks late. Get the delivery date in writing on the purchase order, with a clause that specifies what happens if the supplier misses it (price reduction, free accessories, etc.). This creates accountability without being adversarial.</p>

    <h3>Mistake 10: Skipping the Trial Bake</h3>
    <p>Every oven behaves differently. Hot spots, uneven air circulation, temperature discrepancy between the display and actual baking temperature — these are only discovered by baking real products. Do a full trial bake (multiple product types, multiple temperature settings) before the installation engineer leaves the premises.</p>

