    <h2>Summary: The Procurement Process in Brief</h2>

    <p>Buying bakery equipment in India doesn't have to be the stressful, chaotic experience most bakery owners describe. If you follow a structured process, the risks — overpaying, buying the wrong machine, dealing with unreliable suppliers, post-installation nightmares — are all manageable.</p>

    <p>The single most important principle: <strong>define your requirements before you talk to any supplier.</strong> Know your daily capacity target, your menu, your kitchen dimensions, your power supply, and your budget. Every subsequent decision — which machine, which brand, which supplier, what warranty — becomes straightforward once the requirements are clear.</p>

    <p>If you're unsure where to start, we're happy to help. BakeDesk works with bakeries across India to plan equipment requirements, source from verified suppliers, and navigate the procurement process. There's no obligation — just a conversation about what you're building and what you need to build it.</p>

    <!-- FAQ -->
    <div class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">How long does it take to procure and install bakery equipment in India? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">For Indian-made or locally stocked equipment, delivery and installation typically takes 1–3 weeks from order placement. For imported equipment ordered from overseas, expect 8–16 weeks. European brands (German, French, Italian) often have longer lead times unless the importer stocks the model locally. Always confirm lead time before paying — and add a buffer of 2–3 weeks to your project timeline for unexpected delays. For a new bakery setup, plan your equipment procurement 3–4 months before your planned opening date if you're buying imported equipment.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Can I get bakery equipment on EMI or loan in India? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">Yes. Several financing options are available. MSME loans from public sector banks (SBI, Bank of Baroda, Canara Bank) can be used for bakery equipment under MUDRA or Stand-Up India schemes. Equipment financing from NBFCs like Lendingkart, Kinara Capital, and FlexiLoans is available with faster processing. Some equipment suppliers have tie-ups with financing companies and can arrange equipment loans directly. For GST-registered businesses with 2+ years of ITR history, equipment financing up to ₹1 crore is achievable. Read our full guide: <a href="/blog/bakery-equipment-financing">Bakery Equipment Financing in India</a>.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Should I buy Indian-made or imported bakery equipment? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">It depends on the equipment type and your production requirements. For ovens and large production equipment, imported brands (especially Taiwanese mid-range brands like Sinmag) often offer better build quality and energy efficiency than Indian alternatives at comparable price points. For planetary mixers, spiral mixers, and refrigeration, good Indian-made options exist at lower price points. European brands (German, French, Italian) offer the best quality but at 2–3× the price of Taiwanese or Indian equivalents. For most Indian bakeries, a mix works best: imported ovens for production equipment, Indian-made refrigeration and smallwares for cost efficiency.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">What is a fair warranty period for bakery equipment in India? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">The industry standard in India is 1 year on most commercial bakery equipment. However, this is the minimum acceptable — you should push for 2 years on all major equipment (ovens, mixers) and 5 years on compressors for refrigeration. Heating elements are a common exclusion in 1-year warranties — this is unacceptable; push back. Warranty should cover parts AND labour, not just parts. For equipment above ₹3 lakh, an included first-year AMC (Annual Maintenance Contract) is a reasonable ask.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">How do I find reliable bakery equipment suppliers in India? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">Start with authorised importers for international brands — these are listed on the brand's official website. For Indian brands, look for suppliers who have been in business 10+ years, have a physical showroom, and have GST registration and a proper business address. Always ask for customer references and call them. Trade associations like the Indian Baker's Association or local hotel and restaurant associations often maintain supplier referrals. Attend AAHAR or regional trade shows to meet suppliers in person and see equipment in operation before committing to any purchase.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">What's the minimum equipment needed to start a bakery in India? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">The absolute minimum for a small commercial bakery: a commercial convection oven (4–8 tray, ₹35,000–₹1.5 lakh depending on size), a planetary mixer (10–20 litre, ₹50,000–₹1.5 lakh), a proofing cabinet or improvised proofing system, baking trays and racks, and a display refrigerator if you have a retail front. Budget ₹2–5 lakh for a functional entry-level setup. Read the full cost breakdown: <a href="/blog/bakery-setup-cost-india">Bakery Setup Cost in India 2026</a>.</div>
      </div>

    </div>

